    FirstOrderCollectionImpl, SecondOrderCollectionImpl

    public class KbCollectionImpl
extends KbTermImpl
implements com.cyc.kb.KbCollection
    A KBCollection object is a facade for a #$Collection in Cyc KB. A collection is a thing whose instances share a certain property or feature. A collection is an abstract concept different from an #$Individual. Everything in Cyc KB is either an #$Individual or a #$Collection. The extent of a #$Collection is context dependent.

      • findOrCreate

        public static KbCollectionImpl findOrCreate(String nameOrId)
                                     throws com.cyc.kb.exception.CreateException,
                                            com.cyc.kb.exception.KbTypeException
        Find or create a KBCollection object named nameOrId. If no object exists in the KB with the name nameOrId, one will be created, and it will be asserted to be an instance of #$Collection. If there is already an object in the KB called nameOrId, and it is already a #$Collection, it will be returned. If it is not already a #$Collection, but can be made into one by addition of assertions to the KB, such assertions will be made, and the object will be returned. If the object in the KB cannot be turned into a #$Collection by adding assertions (i.e. some existing assertion prevents it from being a #$Collection), a KBTypeConflictExceptionwill be thrown.
        Parameters:
        nameOrId - the string representation or the HLID of the #$Collection
        Returns:
        a new KBCollection
        Throws:
        com.cyc.kb.exception.KbTypeException
        com.cyc.kb.exception.CreateException

        Find or create a KBCollection object named nameOrId, and also make it an instance of constraintCol in the default context specified by KBAPIDefaultContext#forAssertion(). If no object exists in the KB with the name nameOrId, one will be created, and it will be asserted to be an instance of both #$Collection and constraintCol. If there is already an object in the KB called nameOrId, and it is already both a #$Collection and a constraintCol, it will be returned. If it is not already both a #$Collection and a constraintCol, but can be made so by addition of assertions to the KB, such assertions will be made, and the object will be returned. If the object in the KB cannot be turned into both a #$Collection and a constraintCol by adding assertions, a KBTypeConflictExceptionwill be thrown.
        Parameters:
        nameOrId - the string representation or the HLID of the #$Collection
        constraintCol - the collection that this #$Collection will instantiate
        Returns:
        a new KBCollection
        Throws:
